metadata.name: Hydro Gen #41
metadata.description:
Against the backdrop of texts about valuing water, Hydro Gen charts the ecological devastation and eventual revival of the Tisza river following what has been called one of the gravest environmental disasters in central Europe since Chernobyl.

Nature and humans here are bound within a single frame — havoc in the ecological system activates the breakdown of meaning in the human signifying system of language, but hidden in the wave of ecological disaster is a (re)generative love poem to water that bears witness to its multifaceted beauty and power. A second poem is generated as a soundtrack based on the displayed background text.

- - - - - CLICK TO START SOUND - - - - -

Hydro Gen is a collaborative work conceptualized and developed over the course of one week as part of NFT DEB Generative Dimensions 2022 Hackathon and Conference.

Kalen Iwamoto, lead artist, director

Vitalii Shumanskyi, lead programmer

Nayven Vignette, audio programmer

Tamás Béke, data analysis and visualization

metadata.name: Breakfast #63
metadata.description:
Breakfast is a real-time generative system for creating complex arrangements of primitive forms. Inspired by suprematism, its aim is to arrange simple and boldly coloured shapes in pleasing ways. Driven by a real-time physics engine, it allows for direct collaboration between artist, audience, and generative system. 

Original artwork by Kelly Milligan (kellymilligan.art) in Titirangi, Auckland, New Zealand - Published November 2021 on fxhash.xyz

Upon sale of final token:
- 20% of proceeds will be donated to Forest & Bird (https://www.forestandbird.org.nz/) for conservation efforts within Aotearoa (New Zealand)
- 5% of proceeds will be sent to @liabru (brm.io) for his work on Matter.js

Controls:
- Save: CMD/CTRL + S - Save as a 4096x4096 still image
- Churn*: C or OPTION/ALT + C to toggle churning and direction
- Gravity*: G to toggle gravity
- Bounce*: B to toggle bounciness
* Exclusive to tokens containing the feature

Notes: 
- Churners move for 15s each minute as an abstract clock, disabled by controls

metadata.name: Unfolded #343
metadata.description:
A plane is repeatedly folded over itself, choosing creases either at random, or according to some pattern (like a grid). These creases form the boundaries of the individual textured tiles.

Once the folds are complete, they are undone in reverse order, recreating the original plane. With each unfolding, the orientation of each crease (as a mountain or a valley), and each tile (facing up or down) is recorded as a sequence of 1s and 0s. Tiles are colored and textured according to similarities in these binary sequences, giving rise to subtle symmetries and repetitions.

Written in vanilla JS & HTML5 Canvas.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: glory hole$ #870
metadata.description:
our consciousness as humans can be distilled into a crudely fashioned hole at an abandoned dave & busters and the meditative state that is endured while sitting on a neglected toilet praying for the sound of disrupted waters. glory holes embody anonymity and pleasure for pleasure's sake. they are creations that cannot be destroyed, as they exist in the memories of anyone who uses or witnesses. many speculate that the carving of the hole is the purest form of human ingenuity and the desire to explore the unknown. formerly limited to the physical space. these glory holes transcend space and time. and exist in that same unknown that tempts us all. legalize ground beef. create nothing. consume everything.

HUGE thank you to @PureSpider for the layered PNG template, this dream would not have been realized without you friend.

metadata.name: Nuages possibles #82
metadata.description:
Stippling clouds imagined by a computer.

Each cloud is a "Nuage possible"

It may be generated from code,
but these clouds might have existed,
or might exist in the future,
just for a brief moment.


Those images were inspired by Joanie Lemercier’s cloud series, an algorithm is imagining more and more variations of those skyscapes in an infinite quest for the perfect cloud.

Once created from code, the drawings are made by a plotter machine, a little robot that moves a pen over black paper to lay down dots of white ink. The robot is like an extension of the artist’s arm, allowing him to create infinite iterations and variations.

The dots pattern and their density help create the illusion of shadows, gradients and brightness, a technique inherited from the pointillism movement, born in Belgium and France in the late 19th century.

metadata.name: Textiles #32
metadata.description:
This project attempts to emulate the rich textures of textiles.


High quality export :

Due to the fact that the rendering process is quite CPU/GPU intensive, higher resolution images are divided into tiles. To select the resolution use the following key commands

1 : 1024 x 1024 (1 tile)
2 : 2048 x 2048 (4 tiles)
4 : 4096 x 4096 (16 tiles)
8 : 8192 x 8192 (64 tiles)

To export a tile, press p. Selecting a resolution will restart the tile position to 0. Tiles are ordered column-major order.
